<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Trade Ministers Endorse Algiers Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Winding up their second
ordinary session here Friday, the African trade ministers endorsed
the Algiers Declaration on the upcoming multi-lateral talks with
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The document ensures a common African position for the first
time in the third WTO ministerial meeting, to be held in Seattle,
the United States between November 30 and December 3, 1999, the
Algerian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The African ministers highlighted in the document the
importance of working out a "balanced agenda" for the WTO meeting
that could take into account the interests of all the African
countries and concerns of the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
They called for rectifying the imbalances resulting from the
Uruguay Round and meeting the funding and trade needs of the
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The coming talks of the WTO should seek to promote a regulatory
order that ensures equal sharing of benefits and special treatment
of developing and underdeveloped economies, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The talks should also deal with the African economic problems
in the crucial areas such as agriculture, services, and health.
</P>
<P>
The talks should develop an international trade order that
could support the ongoing economic reforms in the African
countries, the declaration added.
</P>
<P>
It underlined the necessity of extending the WTO interim period
for the intellectual property rights (IPR) and other customs,
trade and investment measures to redress the economic difficulties
effectively.
</P>
<P>
The document also urged for adding more low- and mid-income
African countries to the list of countries enjoying compensations
and favorable treatment.
</P>
<P>
On the WTO membership, the African ministers called for
simplifying and easing the measures and controls imposed on
applicant countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
