<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq on "Humanitarian Intervention" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The so-called
"humanitarian intervention"implies an organized onslaught on the
most fundamental rules of the present international order, such as
sovereignty and political independence, Iraq said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the 54th session of the United
Nations General Assembly, Iraqi Minister of Foreign Affairs Said
Al-Sahaf said the basis of the onslaught was that the said
principles cannot be constitute a protective shield to the grave
violation of human rights, and consequently, intervention, even
with the use of force, should be allowed, in order to protect
those rights.
</P>
<P>
No one should be deceived by this doctrine as being the frame
of the modern picture of colonialism with the logic of power as
its base, Said Al-Sahaf said.
</P>
<P>
"Before anything else, we should realize that there is no
situation in relation to which this doctrine is thrusted which is
free from the external political interference which led to its
existence, and accordingly, it could not be claimed that the
international responsibility for the situation rests exclusively
on the targetted government, " he said.
</P>
<P>
"On the other hand, we should also realize that the purpose and
the principles of the Charter of the United Nations and the
mechanisms of the organization are not devoid of modalities to
deal with any situation of the type advanced to justify the
doctrine," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If it is not unjustified to consider the role of the United
Nations as marginalized after it has become subject to the views
of the controlling powers in international relations and their
selfish interests regardless of what the Charter provides in terms
of rights and duties and procedures, we are convinced that the
doctrine of humanitarian intervention represents a dangerous
destructive tool to all the gains that have been achieved through
joint efforts in favor of the general international interest as
evidenced by the record of this Organization," the Foreign
Minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
