<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies to Install Military Bases in Bolivia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. ambassador in Bolivia Donna
Hrinak denied that her country plans to install a military base in
that country, but revealed that it is negotiating the permanence
of its aircraft in several strategic points of South America.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from Santa Cruz, Bolivia, quoted Hrinak
as saying that U.S. military presence in Bolivia was for
performing social work, and they will leave next week.
</P>
<P>
Evo Morales, a deputy and a leader of coca producing peasants
denounced the arrival of the U.S. military to participate in the
civic operation "New Horizons" in the Chaco of Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said that this operation will benefit the
country because of the training its military personnel will
receive in this region, as much as the El Chaco community, which
will enjoy the works left by the U.S. military specialists.
</P>
<P>
She said that her country is negotiating the installation of
military bases in other countries, but that Bolivia is not
included among them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
