<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cloud over Next Zambian Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Both Zambia's opposition and
ruling parties expressed their concerns over who will contest for
the coming presidential elections in 2001.
</P>
<P>
It is still uncertain whether Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba and its former President Kenneth Kaunda will be rivals in
the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, head of the Zambia's opposition United National
Independence Party (UNIP), said his party has no objection to
President Chiluba to stand for a third term if he is adopted by
his Movement for Multi-Party Democracy (MMD).
</P>
<P>
Basil Kabwe, administrative secretary of the UNIP, said, "we
would like to see him (Chiluba) stand so that we can have a
rematch between Dr. Kaunda and Mr. Chiluba."
</P>
<P>
In return, the ruling MMD has also given Kaunda a green light
to the political arena by saying that it would not stop Kaunda
from contesting for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
MMD National Secretary Michael Sata said: "There equally should
not be any trouble if the MMD field Chiluba for the polls."
</P>
<P>
"We have no problem whom UNIP fields because it's not our
business to stop other parties from putting up candidates of their
choice," Sata said.
</P>
<P>
All political parties are free to choose their presidential
candidates and field them without any problems from other parties,
Sata added.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda ruled the country from its independence in 1964 until
1991, when he was defeated by Chiluba in the multi-party elections
of that year.
</P>
<P>
He was barred from running for the presidency in the elections
held in 1996 because constitutional amendments adopted that year
do not allow those with foreign parentage and those who have
already served two terms of the presidency to stand for elections
any more.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, born of Malawian parents, and his party have been
opposed to the constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
The opposition urged the ruling MMD to remove the clauses in
the constitution to allow the two leaders to contest in the next
elections.
</P>
<P>
President Chiluba has repeatedly stated that he will not
violate the constitution that limits a president to two five-year
terms but recently some MMD officials, especially MMD youth wing,
urged Chiluba to run for a third term and called for a
constitutional amendment to allow Chiluba to do so.
</P>
<P>
However, when asked if he is considering running for the third
term, the president said: "I'm not saying that leaders must not
stay too long but they must justify why they want to stay longer,"
describing the calls for his third term as democracy.
</P>
<P>
Recently some MMD officials, especially MMD youth wing, urged
Chiluba to run and called for a constitutional amendment to allow
him for a third term.
</P>
<P>
MMD youth on the Copperbelt Province held a rally, demanding
Chiluba to stay on, describing him as "a national asset".
</P>
<P>
Copperbelt Province youth Chairman Josiah Mutisa said that
"President Chiluba is a national asset who cannot be allowed to
retire just like that. The MMD and the constitution are not enough
to warrant his departure."
</P>
<P>
The chairman said his members will soon petition other
provinces for a national youth conference so that the idea of
floating President Chiluba in the 2001 elections can be tabled.
</P>
<P>
Copperbelt Deputy Minister Mathew Mulanda said the MMD
leadership is in full support of the youths because there are a
number of things not yet accomplished by Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
On Monday MMD youths in Lusaka Province joined their colleagues
in other provinces calling on Chiluba to stand for another term of
office.  They urged the government to amend the constitution
so as to allow Chiluba to contest the presidency again.
</P>
<P>
Provincial youth chairman Stephen Bwalya said at the gathering
that "the economic situation in our country needs a person of the
current president's calibre for it to forge ahead."
</P>
<P>
Sonny Mulenga, MMD chairman of the Lusaka Province told the
gathering that there is nothing wrong with changing the
constitution as long as the majority of the people favor the
proposed amendments.
</P>
<P>
Mulenga, who is also Lusaka Province Deputy Minister, said that
it has been difficult to find a successor and that Chiluba's
achievements have attracted international support.
</P>
<P>
But chief government spokesman, Information Minister Newstead
Zimba said early this month that the government is not going to
amend the constitution to suit any political party or particular
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda accused early this month Chiluba of being behind "the
growing mild campaign for his third term in office".
</P>
<P>
The UPND and National Citizens Coalition (NCC) are opposed to
the calls for Chiluba's third term of office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
