<HEADLINE> U.S. Officials Expect Kosovo Independence: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Senior U.S. officials have
privately dropped their opposition to Kosovo's independence from
Yugoslavia and say the Clinton administration increasingly sees
the province's secession as inevitable, a leading U.S. newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported from Pristina, Yugoslavia, that
officials say the emerging consensus, which amounts to a major
shift for the U.S., is already having a significant impact on the
international peacekeeping operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The report came one day after NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana said the independence of Kosovo is unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has become a leading advocate for the
creation of independent institutions and legal structures that
tend to isolate the fledging United Nations protectorate from
Yugoslavia's manifold economic problems and political troubles,"
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. officials deny that the administration's
approach is meant to engineer the further breakup of Yugoslavia,
as the Belgrade government claims.
</P>
<P>
The officials added that sovereignty issues should not be
allowed to stand in the way of Kosvo's progress because it will
likely gain its independence anyway.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody in Washington expects this not happen," said a U.S.
official who spoke on condition he not be identified. "Our
attitude before the war was, it's better if it doesn't happen.
Now, we know it's clearly on the way...It's the mostly unspoken
assumption" of all U.S. policy makers.
</P>
<P>
But the newspaper continues to say that Washington declared
that the administration has not altered its policy. The U.S. is
opposed to the independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We support the creation of democratic institutions and a
market economy, and that's the focus of our effort," said a White
House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said, "We have always
said we do not support independence for Kosovo, and we do not
support independence for Kosovo now."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Solana, NATO's top diplomat said that the goal of
Kosovo's ethnic Albanians to gain independence from Yugoslavia is
unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
Solana told a group of American defense reporters that ethnic
Albanians must abandon hope of gaining independence from
Yugoslavia in order to achieve a lasting peace in the divided Serb
province.
</P>
<P>
If the international community allows a shifting of borders in
southern Serbia, it will be hard to stop a momentum toward
political fragmentation elsewhere in the Balkans and perhaps even
in the vast territories of Russia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
