<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President to Wind up U.S. Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa will end his 12-day working visit to the United
States on Saturday, his press secretary Geoffrey Nkurlu said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the Tanzanian President has explained his
country's position on both domestic and international affairs,
according to a statement issued by Nkurlu from Atlanta Friday.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Atlanta, Mkapa visited Boston, Washington D.C.
and New York, meeting businessmen and government officials. He
also addressed the United Nations General Assembly and held talks
with President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Mkapa was conferred a honorary doctorate degree in
humane letters by the President of Morehouse University College.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian President, accompanied by his wife Anna Mkapa,
later visited the Carter Center where he held lengthy talks with
former U.S. President Jimmy Carter. After that, he proceeded to
the Martin Luther King center.  
