<HEADLINE> Cohen to Take Asia-Pacific Trip Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary William
Cohen will start his Asia-Pacific trip next week to Indonesia,
Australia, Thailand, Singapore and the Philippines, the Pentagon
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said Cohen will make his first stop in
Australia, where he will visit the embarkation point for a
peacekeeping force to East Timor in Darwin Wednesday. A great part
of 200 U.S. peacekeeping force are now stationed at the Australian
port.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Cohen will be in Jakarta where he will meet with
Indonesia's President B.J. Habibie and military leader Gen.
Wiranto as well as political opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
"In Jakarta, the secretary will press for military reforms as
well as continuing movement toward fair and democratic elections,"
one senior Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen has no plan to visit East Timor, but the U.S. officials
said he will surely discuss the violence there with Indonesia's
officials.
</P>
<P>
Washington suspended all joint military programs with Indonesia
on Sept. 9 after the eruption of violence in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said this week that Washington would watch the Indonesian
military closely after suspending all the joint military
cooperation programs.
</P>
<P>
"We would hope that reinstitution or rekindling of those
military programs can be achieved at some future time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen will also meet government leaders in Thailand, Singapore
and the Philippines to discuss the security situation in Asia. And
he will return to Washington on Oct. 5, the U.S. officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
