<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Backs Angola's Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China is willing to develop
the fraternal relations with Angola and supports the efforts of
the Angolan people to restore peace and stability in the country,
Chinese Ambassador in Angola said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Yuande made the statement in an interview with the
official newspaper Jornal de Angola on the eve of a grand banquet
in honor of the 50th anniversary of the People's Republic of
China, hailing the "fraternal" Sino-Angolan relations and the
existence of good cooperation and traditional friendship between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the visit by the Angolan President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos to China last year has promoted the bilateral relations
and laid solid foundation for the development of the cooperation
and friendship in the coming 21th century.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said China hopes the war could end as soon as
possible and China will continue to help the Angolan people
reconstruct their homeland.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that China has been abiding by the
decisions made by the United Nations and the U.N. sanctions
imposed on the Angola's rebel National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese contact with UNITA and other movements
in Angola, established at the suggestion of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) during the fight against the Portuguese
colonists, has been ended since the former colony gained
independence from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
As for the humanitarian aid for Angola, Jiang said that in
October, dozens of containers of humanitarian goods offered by
China, including rice, soy and daily necessities, worth more than
600,000 U.S. dollars, will arrive in Angola.
</P>
<P>
China has also provided with an interest-free loan of 11
million U.S. dollars in a housing program for the displaced
Angolan people, which has been started in Viana, a satellite city
of Luanda. In 1999, the Chinese Red Cross provided the Angolan
ministry of social assistance with 20,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
A program on the construction of a modernized 100-bed hospital
in the capital city is under consideration, according to the
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
As for the development of the Chinese economy, Jiang said that
due to the efficient leadership of the Chinese Communist Party,
Chinese economic construction has entered upon a new phase at the
turn of century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
