<HEADLINE> Iraq Appreciates Egypt's Support in Health Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi minister of health on
Friday expressed appreciation for Egypt's support for his country,
especially in the health domain.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has supplied Iraq with medicines and medical equipment it
needed urgently, under the Iraq-United Nations oil-for-food
program, Omed Medhat Mubarak told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks before leaving Cairo for home after
attending the two-day 46th session of the regional office of the
World Health Organization, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under economic sanctions imposed by the U.N. in
1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. It was allowed to export
limited amount of oil to buy food and medicine under a
oil-for-food deal with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Cairo, the Iraqi minister discussed with his
Egyptian counterpart Ismail Sallam steps to implement the joint
minutes agreed upon in Iraq last year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has responded positively to Iraq's demands for more
medicines and medical equipment for its hospitals, the Iraqi
minister added.
</P>
<P>
He said Sallam agreed to send an Egyptian medical team soon to
Iraq to operate on patients for heart diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
The English-language Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported
recently that Egypt will sign with Iraq a deal on the export of 15
million Egyptian pounds (4.41 million U.S. dollars) worth of
medicines and medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has sold to Iraq medicines and medical equipment worth
100 million pounds (29.41 million dollars) since the end of 1996
when the oil-for-food program began to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
It has also set up a permanent center for Egyptian medications
in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad help meet the needs of the Iraqi
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
