<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Receive TOR-M1 Missile Systems: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' National Guard will
in the coming days be receiving an unspecified number of TOR-M1
missile systems, coming from the 21 ordered by Greece from Moscow,
local media reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the National Guard's tank arsenal was likely
to be reinforced both by the American-made M48A5 MOLF and by the
well-known Russian-made T-80.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said the National Guard will be buying from
Russian an additional 43 BMP-3 armored vehicles, two 155 mm
artillery batteries, and 12 long-range multiple rocket launching
systems.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus had planned to buy S-300 missiles from Russia to cement
its air defense capability. But following intense international
pressure and war threats from Turkey, President Glafcos Clerides
had to decide to divert the surface-to-air missiles to Greece's
Crete island last December.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has since been striving to find
alternatives to shore up its air-defense umbrella.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' Defense Minister Socrates Hasikos Thursday ordered an
investigation into leaks to the media about the impending
arrivals of new hi-tech weapons systems for the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
A press release of Cyprus' Defense Ministry said the decision
to investigate the matter is in no way aimed at press freedom;
Rather it adheres to the ministry's policy of protecting important
information vital to national security and defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A new condensate refinery with an investment of
320 million U.S. dollars has started exports of processed
downstream hydrocarbons to global markets, the Dubai-based Gulf
News daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Enoc Processing Co. LLC, located at Dubai's Jebel Ali Free
Zone, is 100 percent owned by the United Arab Emirates National
Oil Co. (Enoc). It is designed to produce 120,000 barrels per day
of diesel oil, fuel, jet fuel, naphtha and liquefied petroleum
gas, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The refinery is producing to its full capacity and we have
started exports mainly to buyers in the Far East and other places
globally," Hussain Sultan, Enoc chief executive officer, was
quoted as saying. He did not specify the volume of exports.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- There could be a sizable demand for computer
peripherals, especially printers, in the Middle East markets
during the last quarter of 1999 and in the first two months of
2000, said the Gulf News daily on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The region's information technology industry forecasts a 20-25
percent growth during the period over the comparable one last
year, industry sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Part of the growth is related to the Y2K compliance issue, but
companies and organizations are also upgrading their peripherals
to match the advances made to their computer systems, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the Middle East is also facing an
acute shortage of computer components, such as memory chips,
motherboards and even processors, which has caused a sharp gain
in component prices.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates continues to be
Thailand's top trade partner in the Middle East, with bilateral
trade last year totaling more than 1.26 billion dollars, and value
in the first seven months of this year reaching 741.7 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Following current trends, the total bilateral trade volume of
1999 is expected to be 5 percent higher than last year, Samroeng
Sampantharak, Middle East director of Thai Trade Center, told Gulf
News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand sources a major portion of its crude oil needs from
the UAE, with shipments in 1998 totaling 665.5 million dollars,
and those in the first seven months of this year at 367.2 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The oil factor has consistently tipped the balance of trade in
the UAE's favor.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The total assets of Lebanese commercial banks rose to
38.5 billion dollars last month from 34.1 billion dollars in
August 1998, an increase of 12.9 percent, the Daily Star reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bank deposits at the end of August stood at 32.4 billion
dollars, 13 percent higher than August 1998, the paper quoted a
Central Bank's report as saying.
</P>
<P>
Total bank loans to the private sector at the end of August
reached 13.5 billion dollars, while loans to the public sector
stood at more than 12 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The European Union (EU) will provide Tunisia 100
million dinars (90.9 million U.S. dollars) in aid to support its
economic reforms between 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The aid is the fourth of its kind from the EU to Tunisia,
according to the Tunisia-Africa News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The assistance, to be delivered on two stages, will be given
soon after the start of economic reforms that cover the banking
sector and the privatization program in education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0022 </DOCNO>
