<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Home Sales Fall for Second Straight Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. sales of existing
homes dropped in August for the second straight month after
hitting a record high in June, the National Association of
Realtors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The association reported that sales of existing single-family
homes fell by 2.8 percent in August to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 5.25 million units.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that mortgage rates rising steadily over the
last six months was probably the major factor.
</P>
<P>
The average rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was 7.94
percent in August, up from 7.63 percent in July and 6.92 percent
in August of 1998, the association said, citing figures from
Freddie Mac, the mortgage company.
</P>
<P>
Last month's sales level was the lowest since May when 5
million units were sold. The decline in August followed a 4
percent drop in sales in July. In June, sales hit an all-time high
of 5.63 million units sold.
</P>
<P>
Despite August's decrease, association officials said they
expect existing homes sales to post another record year in 1999.
Last year's record was 4.97 million units.
</P>
<P>
The 5.25 million level of existing home sales in August are
running about 9.2 percent higher than the sales level in August
1998.
</P>
<P>
The association said that the Northeast was the only part of
the country reporting a gain in sales in August. Sales there rose
7.6 percent to an annual rate of 710,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the national median sales price for existing homes
rose 5.3 percent to a record 137,700 dollars in August over the
same month a year ago, the association said.
</P>
<P>
The association officials attributed the increase in the median
home price to strong demand, a healthy economy and a 29-year-low
unemployment rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Criticizes Cold War Mentality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Friday
criticized the practice of dividing the countries into "coalition
members" and "others" while denying "others" the rights to
development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 54th Session of the U.N. General Assembly,
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said "persistence of Cold War
mentality" serves "certain interests".
</P>
<P>
"During this century, exclusion often surfaced as paradigm of
global interaction. It views the world in terms of modes of
loyalty and belonging into +coalition members+ and +others+, and
divides rewards and blames accordingly," the Minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the mentality reigning in the 20th century has brought
bloodshed and devastation to human society, suppressed many
potentials, wasted much human capabilities and natural resources
and given rise to "domination, autocracy, violence and
confrontation".
</P>
<P>
A dangerous tendency of this approach in the era of
globalization "is the unilateral application of coercive economic
measures and extraterritorial application of domestic legislation
which have been pursued by the United States in spite of unanimous
global opposition," Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. "has an indispensable pivotal role in shaping the new
world of the next millennium", and its enhancement requires
strengthening General Assembly's role by focusing its agenda on
contemporary challenges facing the world, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
