<HEADLINE> EU to Provide New Aid to Tunisia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
provide Tunisia 100 million dinars (90.9 million U.S. dollars) in
aid to support its economic reforms between 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
Tunisian Minister of International Cooperation and Foreign
Investment Mohamed Al-Ghannouchi and visiting Chief of the
European Commission Roubar Holystone signed an accord to this
effect here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The aid is the fourth of its kind from the EU to Tunisia,
according to the Tunisia-Africa News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The assistance, to be delivered on two stages, will be given
soon after the start of economic reforms that cover the banking
sector and the privatization program in education.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony Al-Ghannouchi said the assistance will
enhance the banking sector and increase national income.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Holystone expressed the EU desire to continue
supporting the economic reforms in Tunisia and ensuring the
success of the EU-Tunisian partnership.
</P>
<P>
The EU-Tunisian Partnership Agreement was put into force in
1998, which envisages that EU will extend financial assistance to
Tunisia to bolster its economic competitiveness and privatization
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
