<HEADLINE> Scotland to Win Independence by 2007, Says Nationalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The leader of the
pro-independence Scottish National Party (SNP) predicted on Friday
that Scotland will have gained its independence and broken up
Britain by 2007 -- its 300th birthday.
</P>
<P>
SNP leader Alex Salmond told his party's annual conference,
held in the Scotish city of Inverness, that the death of Britain
-- born in 1707 from the Act of Union between Scotland and England
-- was at hand, the Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Salmond has never before made a prediction about
when Scotland would gain its independence.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Salmond made three key pledges to the people of
Scotland and said independence remains the ultimate goal.
</P>
<P>
He said the nationalists were now established as the main
opposition party in the Scottish Parliament and would ultimately
become Scotland's government.
</P>
<P>
"Our key task as a national party is to make the case for this
parliament becoming a real parliament -- an independent parliament
-- with full powers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Salmond also made a renewed commitment to "fair tax" during his
speech and accused Chancellor Gordon Brown of creating a
multi-billion war chest to offer tax cuts before the next
election.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is different. Spend the resources on the things
that really matter - health education and housing," he said.
</P>
<P>
If Salmond's prediction is to come true, that means the SNP
would have to win the next election for the Edinburgh parliament
in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The party has promised not to hold a referendum on independence
until near the end of a four-year term in charge -- placing the
date for a referendum just before 2007. 
</P>
</TEXT>
