<HEADLINE> Chinese Leaders Involved in Evolution of Dictionary (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Work on the new dictionary started in Shanghai in September,
1958. Numerous experts and scholars joined the comprehensive
effort, producing a "Cihai" that included 100 subjects, such as
politics, economics, culture, military affairs, diplomacy and
religion.
</P>
<P>
The first draft of the new dictionary was completed in March
1960, and in 1965 a draft edition was published. After reading it,
Mao offered his suggestions for changes of some items that
appeared in the publication.
</P>
<P>
The project was suspended at the start of the Cultural
Revolution (1966-1976), but in March, 1971, late Premier Zhou
Enlai announced at a national publication conference that the work
should be renewed.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, leader Deng Xiaoping also urged military departments
to provide written materials and documents detailing battles and
military affairs to be included as references in the dictionary. (
More)
