<HEADLINE> Chinese Leaders Involved in Evolution of Dictionary (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Since the founding of New
China in 1949, generations of Party and government leaders have
been involved in the publishing of the country's largest and most
prestigious dictionary, the "Word Ocean."
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, Chinese president and the general secretary of the
Communist Party of China Central Committee, recently completed a
calligraphic representation of the dictionary's Chinese name "
Cihai" for its 1999 edition.
</P>
<P>
In 1957, Chairman Mao Zedong, the founder of New China, decided
the existing "Cihai" should be re-edited. Mao consulted Shu
Xincheng, a famous Shanghai-based Chinese literature expert who
had compiled a previous edition of the dictionary in 1936 as the
publication's editor-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
"I have been with the dictionary for 20 years, even in battles,
" Mao said, realizing, however, that the old edition contained too
many archaic entries. "It's vital that we publish a new dictionary
for new people, new things and new words in new China," he said.
</P>
<P>
After a few months, Mao again spoke with Shu, who suggested
that when editing of the new "Cihai" was finished, encyclopedia
should be added to the list of China's needed publications.
</P>
<P>
The "Cihai" provides a foundation for the encyclopedia, Mao
said, adding that the entire project would be long-term and
involve Chinese scholars from generation to generation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leaders Involved in Evolution of Dictionary (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1979, the three-part "Word Ocean" was published to mark the
30th anniversary of the founding of New China. At that time, the
country launched the plan to update the dictionary every ten years.
</P>
<P>
The 1989 and 1999 editions have attracted the attention of
President Jiang Zemin, who has encouraged the editors to put
together dictionaries that will be more useful to readers.
</P>
<P>
In his term as Shanghai mayor ten years ago, Jiang produced a
calligraphic representation for the dictionary's 1989 edition to
praise the editors' hard work and outstanding literary skill.
</P>
<P>
Xia Zhengnong, chief editor of the dictionary, said that over
the past 50 years, Chinese leaders as well as dozens of central
governmental departments have shown their interest in and made
considerable contributions to the editing of the "Cihai."
</P>
</TEXT>
