<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Sees Illicit Small Arms Trade Bad to World Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Friday said that the illicit small arms trafficking not
only aggravates the violence associated with terrorism and
organized crime, but also damages development prospects and
imperils human security in every way.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief made the statement at the Security Council's
open ministerial meeting on small arms, which total some 500
million across the world.
</P>
<P>
"The proliferation of small arms, ammunition and explosives has
also aggravated the violence associated with terrorism and
organized crime," he said. "Even in societies not beset by civil
war, the easy availability of small arms has in many cases
contributed to violence and political instability."
</P>
<P>
"These, in turn, have damaged development prospects and
imperiled security in every way," he said. "Indeed, there is
probably no single tool of conflict so widespread, so easily
available, and so difficult to restrict, as small arms."
</P>
<P>
"Not only are they the primary instrument of the murder of
civilians who are increasingly targeted in the wars of our era,"
he said. "Unlike their victims, small arms survive from conflict
to conflict, perpetuating the cycle of violence by their mere
structures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also called on the U.N. Security Council, which
has the primary responsibility for the maintenance of world peace
and security, to devote greater attention to the conflict
prevention and provide effective leadership in this area.
</P>
<P>
"While great challenges still await us, we should take note of
a number of positive development in the struggle against small
arms proliferation, and particularly illicit arms trafficking," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, through an initiative by Mali, the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) declared a moratorium on
the production and transfer of small arms, covering 16 countries.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program (UNDP) is assisting
ECOWAS in implementing that moratorium, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Europe, joint action by the European Union in preventing
and combatting illicit trafficking in conventional arms is
another promising step, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"More specifically, in Albania, the UNDP, in close
collaboration with the Department for Disarmament Affairs, has
been engaged in a 'Weapons for Development' project," he said.
"The success of that pilot project has encouraged the Albanian
Government to invite similar projects in other parts of Albania."
</P>
<P>
And in America, the Organization of American States adopted in
November 1997 the Inter-American Convention against the Illicit
Manufacturing of and Trafficking in Firearms, Ammunition,
Explosives and Other Related Materials.
</P>
<P>
"The momentum for combatting small arms proliferation has also
come from civil society, which has been increasingly active on
this issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment early this year of the International Action
Network on Small Arms helped to sharpen public focus on small
arms, which has helped us gain the public support necessary for
success," he said.
</P>
<P>
In order to develop the international consensus on the small
arms, the United Nations plans to convene an international
conference on illicit small arms trade in 2001.
</P>
<P>
"The international community must seize the opportunity by the
international conference in the year 2001 to demonstrate its
political will and its commitment to reversing the global
proliferation of small arms," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholar On Social Development in 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua)-- The international society will
enter an age of knowledge-based economy in the 21st century, which
is called the "second modernization progress," a Chinese scholar
told a seminar today on social development in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"If the progress from the farming age to the industrial age is
the 'first modernization progress,' the advancement from the
industrial era to the knowledge era can be named the 'second
modernization progress'," said He Chuanqi, a research fellow with
the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
He said that the second modernization progress will be marked
by knowledge, computers and international cooperation, while the
characteristics of the first are industrialization, urbanization
and democratization.
</P>
<P>
"In a word, the first one is conquering the nature and the
second one is returning to the nature," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also presented his tentative plan on China's second
modernization progress, saying that the latest knowledge
renovation has given China new developing opportunities and
challenges, which demands the country accomplish the modernization
progress in the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of scholars from academic units such as the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, Beijing University and Qinghua
University attended the seminar. They affirmed that He's new
theory is rational and creative though it still needs some
revision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
