<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministers to Discuss Tariff Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Economic ministers of member
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
will meet next week to discuss tariff reductions, a senior
official from Thailand's Commerce Ministry said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Karun Kittisataporn, director-general of the Department of
Business Economics, said that the issue of accelerating tariff
cuts of products among ASEAN members to zero to five percent by
the year 2000 would be on the top agenda of the 31st Meeting of
ASEAN Economic Ministers, to be held between September 27 to
October 2 in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
According to the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) starting from
January 1, 2000, ASEAN members will reduce tariff rates on 85
percent of their goods to between zero and five percent.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, 85 percent of its good amount to 7,777 items,
Karun said.
</P>
<P>
"At the meeting, Thailand will also submit an additional list
of 1,190 items of products that are subject to tariff reductions
to the zero to five percent by next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members had also agreed to begin reducing import tariffs
of non-processed agricultural products in the sensitive and
highly-sensitive groups to zero to five percent between 2001 and
2003 so that the products would be fully liberalized by January 1,
2010, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tariff reduction for rice, which is a highly-sensitive
non-processed farm product, would be begun between 2001 and 2005
so that it would be fully liberalized by January 1, 2010, he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
