<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reaffirms Willingness to Provide Aid to Taiwan Compatriots ( RECAST) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China today reaffirmed its
willingness to provide any necessary aid to its Taiwan compatriots
to help reduce the losses caused by the strong quake that hit the
island Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jincheng, vice-president and secretary-general of the
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS),said
that after knowing the quake rocked Taiwan, a rescue team,
comprised of noted seismologists, disaster relief experts, and a
medical team of the mainland were formed and were ready to leave
for Taiwan. He expressed the wish that the Taiwan side would allow
them to enter Taiwan as soon as possible so that they could render
their help.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that shortly after the quake on Tuesday morning,
Chinese President Jiang Zemin sent his condolence to the Taiwan
compatriots and expressed the mainland's willingness to provide
all necessary aid.
</P>
<P>
He said the ARATS, authorized by the mainland, on Tuesday sent
a letter to Taiwan's Foundation for Exchange Across the Taiwan
Strait regarding aid to the quake-struck areas.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the State Council also issued a circular, asking local
departments to facilitate those Taiwan compatriots who wish to go
back to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
But Taiwan's response on Thursday evening made it clear that
the mainland's relief plan would not be carried out as planned,
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Sun Aimin, secretary-general of the Red Cross Society of China,
said his society is deeply concerned about the situation in Taiwan
and is looking forward to starting its rescue work in Taiwan in
accordance with the Red Cross's spirit of humanism and neutrality.
</P>
<P>
Though the Taiwan Red Cross has said that no aid in the forms
of personnel or materials is needed at present, Sun said his
organization would continue to closely monitor the situation in
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross Society of China will also work closely with its
international counterparts to support relief efforts for Taiwan
compatriots.
</P>
<P>
He Yongnian, head of the Across-Straits Seismological Exchange
Center, said seismologists on the mainland are looking forward to
join their Taiwan counterparts in monitoring the aftershocks and
providing technical support.
</P>
<P>
Li Bengong, head of the China Disaster Mitigation and Relief
Association, said his association and all disaster relief
organizations across the country are also ready to render
humanitarian aid to the quake-struck areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
