<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Troops In Congo Expected to Go Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean troops deployed
in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) can be expected to
go home at anytime as peace in the war-torn central African
country is at hand.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Defense Minister Moven Mahachi made these remarks
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi said: "As soon as the United Nations peace-keepers
arrive in the DRC, a timetable would be drawn for the withdrawal
of the allied forces."
</P>
<P>
But, "we cannot withdraw immediately because the enemy is still
in position," the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted the defense minister
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations had already started to deploy
military liaison officers in Zambian capital Lusaka and Rwandan
capital Kigali to monitor the cease-fire agreement for the DRC.
</P>
<P>
So far, the cease-fire had been holding as only isolated
movements of rebels had been reported and the allied forces was
monitoring the situation closely, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi also called for the private sector to take advantage of
the goodwill fostered by the Zimbabwean Defense Forces during the
intervention in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
He said that the defence forces had formed a civilian company
which, with a sister company in the DRC, would act as facilitators
for potential investors in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
This was in line with efforts by the defense forces to try to
find income-generating projects to boost its strained funds, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean business people can explore business opportunities
in such areas as tourism, transport and mining, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
