<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 48% Russians See Brezhnev Epoch as Golden Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of all Russians
recently polled regard Leonid Brezhnev's epoch as "a golden era"
when "ordinary people" lived best of all, the Interfax news agency
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The idea was held by 48 percent of respondents to the poll
conducted by the Public Opinion fund among 1500 urban and rural
areas on September 4.
</P>
<P>
The respondents were asked to choose the Russian leaders in the
20th century under whom "ordinary people live best of all." They
were given nine names, from Tsar Nicholas II to incumbent
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
The pollsters also posed another question related to elections:
if any 20th century Russian leader or eminent contemporary Russian
politician (18 were listed) ran for president today, for whom
would you vote for?
</P>
<P>
Brezhnev and his successor, Yuri Andropov, enjoyed the highest
support with 12 percent. Among the current politicians, most
respondents' support would be given to ex- Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov (10 percent) and Russian Communist Party Leader Gennady
Zyuganov (7 percent). Joseph Stalin was also favored by 7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
