<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Accused of Insisting on Anti-Cuba Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Cuba on Friday accused
the United States of continuing to act against the international
call for ending the U.S. imposed economic blockade targeting the
republic in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 54th Session of the U.N. General Assembly,
Foreign Minister Felipe Perez Roque said the 40-year sanctions
have dealt a savage blow to his country's major source of
employment and revenue and depriving it of essential funds for
acquiring food, medicine, fuel and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The blockade has gone as far as to prevent Cuba from importing
even a U.S.-made aspirin or exporting to the U.S. a single flower
cultivated in Cuba, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992 the U.N. General Assembly has consistently adopted a
resolution on the necessity of ending the blockage, amid
international condemnation of the U.S. "genocidal policy", he
added.
</P>
<P>
The support for Cuba has grown from year to year with the
resolution receiving votes from 59 in 1992 to 157 in 1998 while
the U.S. has managed to obtain only 3 or 2 votes over the years,
the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Based on the 1948 U.N. Convention on the Prevention and
Punishment of the Crime of Genocide, Cuba's parliament decided 11
days ago that the Cuban courts have the right to try and punish
the parties guilty of "genocidal" activities against Cuba, Perez
Roque said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.N. Increases Concerns on Small Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Friday convened an open meeting on the proliferation of
small arms, which, though small in size and light in weight, have
created big casualties in the world today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held at the ministerial meeting during the general
debate of the 54th General Assembly session, shows the growing
concerns of the United Nations on small arms.
</P>
<P>
More than tanks, missiles and mortars, one half billion small
arms and light weapons are circulating in the world today. They
are responsible for killing three million people in the last
decade alone. No fewer than 8 of every 10 people killed were
children and women.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, long focused on nuclear weapons and
conventional disarmament, has become increasingly concerned over
the role of small arms, particularly in internal conflicts and in
the hands of insurgents, criminals and terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
From the Balkans to East Asia and to Africa, small arms have
become the instrument of choice for the killers in the current
world.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Security Council, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said, "The proliferation of small arms, ammunition and
explosives has also aggravated the violence associated with
terrorism and organized crime. Even in societies not beset by
civil war, the easy availability of small arms has in many cases
contributed to violence and political instability."
</P>
<P>
These, in turn, have damaged development prospects and
imperiled human security in every way. "Indeed, there is probably
no single tool of conflict so widespread, so easily available, and
so difficult to restrict, as small arms," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report to the Security Council, Annan said,
"Small arms are widely used in conflicts in which a high
proportion of the casualties are civilians, and in which violence
has been perpetrated in gross violation of international
humanitarian law."
</P>
<P>
"This has led to millions of deaths and injuries, the
displacement of populations, and suffering and insecurity around
the world," he said. "While regions such as Africa and the
Americas have been affected more than others, the proliferation of
small arms and light weapons knows no boundaries."
</P>
<P>
Small arms were defined as weapons designed for personal use,
such as revolvers, rifles, carbines, sub-machine guns, assault
rifles and light machine guns.
</P>
<P>
Light weapons, designed for use by a crew of several persons,
range from heavy machine guns and portable anti-aircraft and
anti-tank guns and missile launchers, to mortars of less than 100
millimeter calibre.
</P>
<P>
Globally, it has been estimated that more than 500 million
small arms and light weapons are in existence, a U.N. report said,
adding that "they continue to be produced in large numbers: mostly
in developed countries, though they are now manufactured on an
industrial scale in more than 70 countries and in numerous
countries as a craft industry."
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the major U.S. newspaper "Washington Post"
reported the U.S. efforts to export small arms to the outside
world through various kinds of ways and means, thus becoming a
dominant force on the world small arms market.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has played a leading role in raising
awareness and understanding of the excessive and destabilizing
accumulation and transfer of small arms and light weapons, and in
promoting international efforts to address this problem.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the General Assembly requested the Secretary-General
to prepare a report with the assistance of a panel of experts on
the nature and causes of such accumulation and transfers and on
ways and means to prevent and reduce them.
</P>
<P>
This report acted as a catalyst to place the issue of small
arms and light weapons firmly on the international agenda, and the
United Nations has continued to encourage and support all efforts
to address the wide-ranging problems posed by such weapons.
</P>
<P>
U.N. experts made some new recommendations, some of which
fairly obvious, ranged from urging states to "exercise the
utmost restraint in transfers" of small arms and ammunition to
areas of conflict, to ensuring weapons carry markings to
identify their country of origin and the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
Another proposal was that "practical disarmament measures
should be developed and adopted in Kosovo related to small arms
and light weapons collection."
</P>
<P>
An earlier recommendation was for the United Nations to help
convene an inter-Afghan forum aimed at retrieving and destroying
small arms left unaccounted for in that civil war-ravaged country
once national reconciliation is reached.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations plans to hold an international conference on
the illicit arms trade by 2001 in order to develop international
consensus on ways and means to effectively combat and prevent
illicit arms trafficking and transfers of small arms and light
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
