<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Sovereignty Over Efforts to Solve Small  Arms Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China said here Friday
that the international community, when trying to solve the
problems caused by small arms, should fully respect the
sovereignty of countries concerned and refrain from interfering in
the internal affairs of countries in conflict.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Wang Guangya, assistant foreign minister
of China, was addressing an open meeting at the Security Council on
small arms.
</P>
<P>
"In trying to solve the problems caused by small arms, the
international community should fully respect the sovereignty of
countries concerned and refrain from interfering in the internal
affairs of countries in conflict regions so as to avoid further
complicating the matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While efforts are being stepped up to eliminate the adverse
impact of small arms, full consideration should be given to the
rightful self-defense an security needs of countries and guarantee
their legitimate right to possess, manufacture and transfer small
arms," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the United Nations peackeeping and post-conflict
peace-building process, weapons confiscation and disposal measures
should be carried out strictly within given mandate with due
respect to and compliance of the agreement and arrangement reached
voluntarily among parties concerned," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of small arms arises from rather complex roots and
covers wide and diversing areas," he said. "It is imperative to
treat both the root cause and the symptom of the problem and carry
out incisive analysis of the cause."
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the excessive accumulation and illegal
transfer of small arms have intensified the conflict in some
regions and caused civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
"The international community, including the United Nations, has
taken various measures to reduce and ultimately eliminate the
negative impact of small arms," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China exercises strict control on the manufacturing and export
of small arms," he said. The Chinese Government promulgated laws
on gun control and mangement of military material export in 1996
and 1998 respectively.
</P>
<P>
"China has scored outstanding achievement in cracking down on
the illegal manufacturing and smuggling of guns," he said. "It is
willing to join the international efforts in solving the problem
of small arms at an early date." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
