<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Eliminating Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Friday urged the joint efforts from both the
developed and developing countries in reducing and eliminating
absolute poverty in the world.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Ministerial Meeting of the Group of 77, Annan
said the central challenges facing the Group of 77 and its
development partners could be summarized in two words, development
and peace.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the violence and social tensions which afflicted so
many developing countries were caused, in part at least, by
deprivation and inequality.
</P>
<P>
The key decisions had to be taken by national government, in
both developed and developing countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is they who must focus their energies on implementing the
measures to which they had already agreed, on both the national
and international levels," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"At the national level, governments must give priority to
job-creation strategies, in the countryside as well as the cities,
while carrying out structural reforms and promoting private sector
development," he said,
</P>
<P>
"The developed countries must take the actions needed to
provide higher levels of development assistance, debt relief, and
improved market access to the developing countries." the U.N.
chief said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations would continue to focus it energies and
resources on the task of reducing and eliminating the absolute
which had condemned so many millions of the people to a life of
misery and degradation, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
