<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Doctors Urged to Return to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Friday asked the country's junior doctors to end the strike
they have undertaken since Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told a press conference in Harare that he was aware of
the doctors' demand for raising salary but opposed to strike.
</P>
<P>
"The strike is a sad development and one obviously regrets that
the doctors resorted to such an action. Their argument cannot be
flowed but their action cannot be condoned. I demand that they go
back to work," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of junior doctors, the backbone of the country's
medical system for the majority poor, went on strike demanding a
review of their salaries, an increase in allowances and
improvement of their working conditions.
</P>
<P>
The strike which entered into the fourth day on Friday had
spread to all parts of the country, paralyzing major hospitals'
operation.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Health and Child Welfare Minister Timothy
Stamps also called on striking junior doctors to return to work
and save lives of sick people.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he sympathized with the grievances of junior
doctors but they should call off the industrial action because
people were dying in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Stamps could not be drawn to say what his ministry was doing to
stop the strike. 
</P>
