<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Develops New Strategy For Environmental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has
announced a new strategy to address the environmental challenges
facing the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The strategy will build on the bank's mission to fight
poverty, according to the Annual Review of the Environment
released by the bank here Friday.
</P>
<P>
More emphasis will be placed on addressing the environmental
factors that cause health problems such as air and water
pollution, the review said.
</P>
<P>
There will be greater attention to the management of natural
resources such as soil, forests, water and fish -- the life
support systems on which people's livelihoods depend.
</P>
<P>
In addition the strategy will focus on the increasing
vulnerability to natural disasters -- especially of poor
communities -- provoked by flooding and other extreme weather
phenomena.
</P>
<P>
"A great deal has been accomplished over the past decade but
the time has come to recast the challenge," said Ian Johnson,
vice-president for environmentally and socially sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
"We must both broaden and deepen our approach. Broaden by
working more effectively to address degradation of our natural
resource base, integrating environmental concerns into
macroeconomic policy, and dealing better with the challenges
posed to poor people by the global problems of climate change
and loss of biodiversity," Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
"Deepen by doing a lot more on the basic problems of air
pollution and the lack of access to safe water and sanitation that
continue to dog the lives of poor people the world over," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The new approach reflects the growing consensus that the
environmental agenda should be more closely linked to the
overall development objectives of the developing world with a
focus on impacts and outcomes rather than inputs and processes.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 Annual Review documented the evolution of the bank's
environmental agenda which began with a "do no harm" approach
through the development of safeguard policies on environmental
assessment.
</P>
<P>
In many cases, according to the review, environmental
assessments and compliance with other so-called safeguard policies
had led to better project design and environmental management.
</P>
<P>
To reinforce efforts in this domain, the bank has just
established a new Quality Assurance and Social Safeguard Unit to
ensure that all projects meet its environmental and social
safeguard policies.
</P>
<P>
During the 1990s the bank developed a portfolio of projects
with clear environmental objectives which now amounts to some 15
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Over the past fiscal year, 23 projects with environmental
objectives were approved, amounting to 2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The bank's environmental agenda has shifted over the year
since the Rio Earth Summit in response to the stubborn fact that
poor people continue to bear the brunt of environmental
degradation through ill health, exposure to natural catastrophes
and the destruction of their life-support systems," said Robert
Watson, World Bank director for environment.
</P>
<P>
"We and many others have worked hard to address these
problems over the past decade. But it has not been enough. We
are now focusing our efforts to have maximum impact where there
is maximum need," Watson said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0061 </DOCNO>
