<HEADLINE> Chile Denies Pinochet Case Affects Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chile said Friday that the
case of lifetime senator Augusto Pinochet will not affect the
country's economic relations with Spain.
</P>
<P>
Hector Casanueva, Foreign Ministry Commercial Office director,
said that even if Pinochet's extradition to Spain is approved, the
citizens of that European country can continue investing in Chile.
</P>
<P>
During the discussion about the all-time increase of economic,
trade and financial relations between Spain and Chile, held here
this week, Casanueva said that Spaniards and Chileans continue
doing business every day.
</P>
<P>
"There is no setback in the relations between Spain and Chile
in the matter of commerce and investments, since the controversy
about the detention of Pinochet has been restricted to the
diplomatic, political, and judicial fields.
</P>
<P>
Augusto Pinochet, charged with crimes against humanity
committed during the 1973-1990 military regime, has been detained
in London since last October. Spain wants him to be extradited to
its soil for trial. A hearing on the request is to begin on
September 27. 
</P>
