<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Italian Premier Acquitted of Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Former Italian Premier Giulio
Andreotti and five co-defendants were acquitted Monday evening of
the charge of murdering an investigative reporter in Rome in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The verdict was handed down in the central Italian city of
Perugia at the end of a trial which opened here on April 11, 1996,
and five days of deliberations on the prosecution and defense
arguments in chambers by two professional judges and six jury
members from the general public.
</P>
<P>
Andreotti, 79, the nation's leading Christian Democratic
politician and Italian premier for seven times when the Catholic
party dominated the national political scene until 1994, was
indicted in July 1995 on the charge of complicity in the murder of
Carmine (Mino) Pecorelli on March 20, 1979, with a former
magistrate and cabinet minister, Claudio Vitalone.
</P>
<P>
Four others -- two Mafia bosses and the two alleged murderers
-- were also told in November 1995 to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
The Mafia dons named were Gaetano Badalamenti, in prison in the
United States, and Giuseppe Calo, killed in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Those charged with carrying out the shooting were the hit-man
reportedly preferred by Bontade, Michelangelo La Barbera, and
Massimo Carminati.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution had asked for Italy's stiffest sentence, life
imprisonment, for all six.
</P>
<P>
According to the prosecution, the most famous and reputedly
most reliable of the Mafia informants, Tommaso Buscetta, said that
Pecorelli was killed because he was about to publish revelations
that could hurt Andreotti's political career.
</P>
<P>
In initial testimony to Palermo prosecutors in 1993, Buscetta
said Andreotti had asked old-guard Mafia bosses Bontade and
Badalamenti to get rid of the journalist who was bothering him. He
said he had learned this from the bosses.
</P>
<P>
Buscetta subsequently modified his testimony to say that both
Bontade in 1980 and Badalamenti two years later told him the
murder was performed "in the interests" of Andreotti.
</P>
<P>
After the delivery of the verdict, he said, "I'm a bureaucrat
and, basically, the commitments I had I maintained." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
