<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 39.26 at
10,279.33. The blue chip index lost 524.30 points, or 4.9 percent,
in the past week and dropped 1,946.71 points, or 9.2 percent,
below its record closing high of 11,326.04 set August 25.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 3.05 at 1,277.36 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 9.42 at 2,740.41.
</P>
<P>
The remarks by Microsoft president Steve Ballmer on stocks
overvaluation continued to hit the market Friday. Ballmer said
Thursday that the technology stocks, including Microsoft's, are
overvalued.
</P>
<P>
The market was also affected by the earthquake in the Taiwan
region. Investors worried that the earthquake will hurt computer
chips production because Taiwan's semiconductor output accounts
for about 10 percent of the world market.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.44 at 589.54 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 5.71 at 771.79. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 3.12 at 417.09.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,824 down, 1,172 up and 529
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 866.10 million shares from 873.98
million in the previous session. 
