<HEADLINE> N.Irish Republicans, Unionists Review Strategies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's pro-British
unionist and pro-Irish republican parties met separately in
Scotland and Ireland Saturday to review their strategy ahead of a
new round of peace talks set for next week.
</P>
<P>
Members of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, gathered in the west of the Republic of Ireland
this weekend for a think-tank on the state of the peace process
and the peace talks chaired by former U.S. senator George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell left Belfast for the United States Thursday after the
latest round of talks but plans to return next Wednesday. Mitchell
said before his departure that he was confident his initiative
would succeed.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists, also took
members of his party to Glasgow, Scotland, for a weekend
conference to plan their participation in Mitchell's talks and
discuss whether the deadlock -- over IRA disarmament -- can be
broken.
</P>
<P>
The meeting comes days after Trimble was accused of giving
"mixed signals" by supporting a legal challenge to Northern
Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlem's ruling that the IRA ceasefire is
intact, and then subsequently meeting Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary in any sort of situation to be able to step
back and have a think about the situation and consider one's
overall strategy. It's something we do from time to time," said
Trimble, who is Northern Ireland's first-minister designate under
structures set up by the Good Friday accord signed in April last
year.
</P>
<P>
But Trimble's deputy party leader, John Taylor, who is
boycotting the Mitchell talks, did not attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein says Trimble's refusal to share power with it in a
planned coalition government unless the IRA disarms is a breach of
the Good Friday accord. Trimble says the IRA must disarm as proof
that it has ended its long war against British rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
