<HEADLINE> EU Education Ministers Meet in Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Finland hosted a ministerial
conference on education cooperation between EU members Friday,
official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting between EU ministers of education was a
prelude for a formal ministerial conference scheduled late in
November.
</P>
<P>
The ministers attending the meeting agreed that reforms for
educational systems are needed to strengthen educational
cooperation between EU countries, and to enhance the quality of
education.
</P>
<P>
The ministers discussed the "rolling agenda" proposed by
Finland, an approach to arranging educational policy that exceeds
EU presidential requirements. The ministers welcomed it as an
approach that could effectively promote exchanges of educational
experience and information among EU member countries, and lead to
decisions on long-term educational policy.
</P>
<P>
In the outline for EU Education 2000-2004, Viviane Reding,
recently elected EU commissioner of education, stressed the
importance of foreign language study for children under the age of
four.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign language education for children is of crucial
importance for the future of the EU," said Reding, who speaks
seven languages.
</P>
<P>
The issue of education is the focus of the month: Finland
hosted ministerial conferences on lifetime education, on the job
training, and higher education in September. 
</P>
