<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Oriental Rugby" Fantastic in China's National Minorities Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Players of the Red Team were
scattering to make another attack towards the goal area of the
Blue side, with every player seemingly holding something near his
stomach.
</P>
<P>
Before the Blues managed to find out the "Huapao", the one who
carried it has reached the goal area and scored.
</P>
<P>
This is a fantastic scene of a game called "Qiang Huapao", or "
Grab Firecracker". Nick-named Oriental Rugby, it is one of the
fantabulous sports at the on-going Chinese National Games for
Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Huapao" is the ball of the game. Made of rubber in the shape
of a disc, it is 14 centimeters in diameter, 2.5 to three
centimeters thick and weighs about 220-240 grams. It is blasted
to mid-air by a throwing machine at the start of each game and
after each goal.
</P>
<P>
The playing field is 60 meters long and 50 meters wide, with
two teams of eight players each competing in two halves, 20
minutes each.
</P>
<P>
A goal is counted for a team when any of its players carrying
the "Huapao" passes the central section of the touch line or puts
it into a basket behind the line. A bamboo fence vertical to the
touch line is installed at each end of the section to prevent
players from entering the goal area other than doing so from
inside the field. The team with more goals at the end of the game
is declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
"Qiang Huapao" was initiated in tribes of the Zhuang and Dong
Nationalities in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
"Huapao" was blasted to mid-air by a powder explosion for the
popular game usually played by scores of people at an annual
festival on March 3 in lunar Chinese calendar. The one who
finally obtained the "Huapao" would present it to the chief of the
tribe to be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
The game was later transformed and was introduced as a medal
sport at the National Minorities Games in 1986. The firecracker
has been replaced by the rubber disc, for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
The competitions at the Beijing Games have attracted a field of
11 teams from various Chinese provinces, municipalities,
autonomous regions and units of Chinese army PLA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0084 </DOCNO>
