<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Warn Against Collapse of Mideast Peace Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Saturday
warned that the Middle East peace process would collapse unless
Jerusalem restores its status and its islamic feature.
</P>
<P>
The league issued the warning in a statement released by its
general secretariat one day ahead of the Jerusalem Day.
</P>
<P>
The Arab nation has opted for peace as a strategic goal, said
the 22-nation pan-Arab forum. But the cherished objective will not
be realized until an independent Palestinian state is established
with Jerusalem as its capital, the league said.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Day marks Israel's digging of a tunnel under Al
Aqsa Mosque in the city four years ago which sparked violent
protests and demonstrations by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel's attempts to Judaize the holy city are "null and void"
and "could not change the status of Jerusalem" as Muslim's third
holiest site, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli practices are unilateral moves that are aimed at
imposing a fait accompli and pre-judging the final-status
negotiations between the Palestinians and Israel, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has never ceased perpetrations in Jerusalem since its
occupation, which are marked by violations of the relevant United
Nations resolutions on the status of the holy city and oppressions
against Palestinian residents and lands.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolutions stipulate that Jerusalem is under control
of the world organization. But Israel occupied the whole of the
city in two Arab-Israeli wars and declared in 1980 that it is "the
eternal and undivided" capital of Israel. The Palestinians want
traditional Arab East Jerusalem as capital of their future
independent state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel began negotiations for a final
peace agreement on issues including the status of Jerusalem and
Palestinian statehood on September 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern China's Tide-Watching Festival Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The festival has been held annually since 1994 and has
attracted millions of tourists to Haining on the northern bank of
river, and Xiaoshan on the southern bank.
</P>
<P>
The tide of the Qiantang River near Haining is one of China's
most amazing phenomena. Scientists say that the bell-shaped mouth
of the Qiantang River near the city helps form the not-to-be-
missed "Haining Tide," which has a crest of as high as 3.5 meters.
</P>
<P>
In the past, only the Mid-Autumn Festival, which falls on
September 24 this year, was considered a good time for tide-
watching, but scientists say that the spring tide on Qiantang
River is also worth a look.
</P>
<P>
Numerous activities have been arranged in conjunction with the
tide-watching, organizers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
