<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua)-- Folowing are highlights of
today's diplomatic news released by Xinhua:
</P>
<P>
 MOFTEC Minister Leaves for Washington for WTO Talks
</P>
<P>
A Chinese delegation, led by Shi Guangsheng, minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation, left here today for
Washington to resume negotiations on China's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO) at the invitation of U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue said on Friday that
the U.S. has recently repeatedly expressed its wish to resume
negotiations with China on WTO entry, and U.S. President Bill
Clinton also formally asked Chinese President Jiang Zemin to re-
open the talks.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese FM Back from UN General Assembly
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan returned to Beijing today after
attending the 54th UN General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Tang delivered a speech at the general debate of the General
Assembly, expounding on the Chinese government's position on the
present world situation and offering suggestions on the
establishment of a new world political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
He also held talks with foreign ministers of the European Union
Troika, the Group of Rio, and the Gulf Cooperation Council, and
met with counterparts from some African countries.
</P>
<P>
 MOFTEC Official on Economic Ties With Africa
</P>
<P>
China and African nations are witnessing a growing cooperation
in economic and trade, labor service contracting and technological
areas, Sun Guangxiang, vice-minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation (MOFTEC), said here today.
</P>
<P>
Sun made the remark during the closing ceremony of the third
China-Africa Seminar for Economic and Management Officials.
</P>
<P>
Sun cited the seminar as a "new channel" for bilateral economic
ties, which provides both officials and businessmen of the two
sides with an opportunity to increase exchanges, mutual
understanding and friendship.  
</P>
