<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai GM Rolls out 10,000 Buicks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai General Motors (SGM)
, the largest Sino-US joint venture in China, rolled the 10,000th
Buick sedan car off its production line here today, with SGM
managers announcing that the company has already received orders
of 15,000 of the cars.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the convocation of the Fortune Global Forum here
from September 27 to 29, General Motors, one of the world's
largest companies, has set yet another record in China's auto
industry. It took SGM less than six months to almost reach its
planned daily capacity of production after regular production
started in April.
</P>
<P>
GM President and Chief Executive Officer Richard Wagoner will
arrive in Shanghai to attend the Fortune Global Forum on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Rudolph Shlais, vice-president of GM, said here today that the
SGM is the highest-level strategic project in General Motors
outside North America. He said that the joint-venture is also
expected to be the most successful project of GM around the world.
</P>
<P>
"As the largest auto company in the world, General Motors
believes that in order to maintain our global leadership, we must
also be a leader in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Many economists predict that in the next 20 to 25 years, the
Chinese auto market will grow to be one of the largest auto
markets in the world--we have every confidence that it will," he
told more than 600 Chinese and international guests attending the
10,000-car celebration ceremony this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
SGM has a total investment of 1.5 billion US dollars. SGM will
begin production of a seven seat wagon in May, 2000. Efforts are
being made to achieve 60 percent domestically produced parts for
its Buick sedan cars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
