<HEADLINE> Burundian President Arrives in Rwanda for One-Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Burundian President Pierre
Buyoya arrived in Rwanda Saturday morning for a one-day visit to
the country, Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The president, accompanied by Minister of Energy and Mines
Bernard Barandereka and Minister of Agriculture Patrice Ntihabose,
was greeted by his Rwandan counterpart Pasteur Bizimungu at
Kanombe International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Buyoya immediately had talks with Bizimungu
and Rwandan Vice President Paul Kagame.
</P>
<P>
The current visit to Rwanda by Buyoya, which follows a similar
visit to Burundi by Bizimungu last week, is in the framework of
bilateral exchanges relating to mutual cooperation and the
situation in the Great Lakes region, RNA quoted official sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We want to meet the Rwandan leaders for consultations about
the problems of the region, and how some of them can be solved,"
Buyoya told reporters before taking off for the Rwanda capital
Kigali.
</P>
<P>
He added that his visit is aimed at explaining Burundi's peace
process in an effort to seek Rwanda's support.
</P>
<P>
Burundi is currently facing an upsurge of rebel activities in
the capital Bujumbura and some other areas of the country,
especially in provinces bordering Tanzania where the six-year old
ethnic conflict has up to now claimed the lives of more than
200,000 people, mostly civilians.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Buyoya's visit will be sanctioned by a
joint communique and a press briefing at Kanombe Airport late
Saturday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
