<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Former President Says Modern China in Shape (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 25 (Xinhua) -- In the eyes of former
Tanzanian president Ali Hassan Mwinyi, China is historically a
civilized nation as well as a modern country gradually taking
shape.
</P>
<P>
"China had held a prominent position in world affairs even
before the creation of modern China 50 years ago. Civilization has
existed for a long time in China as evidenced by the presence of
the ancient monuments such as the Great Wall, as well as the
numerous fortifications and temples," Mwinyi told Xinhua during a
recent interview at his residence.
</P>
<P>
The former president's residence is a three-story white
building located in a garden-like courtyard in the northern
outskirts of the Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam. The 74-year-old
statesman was sitting barefooted in a parlor with a marble floor.
</P>
<P>
Mwinyi said he expects to see more changes in the Asian giant
when he visits Beijing to attend the 50th anniversary of the
People's Republic of China on October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
"Trade, industry and cultivation were far ahead in China many
years ago before some of the Western industrialized countries were
formed," said Mwinyi. "China was the envy of the world, prompting
Western explorers and travelers like Marco Polo to brave the seas
and oceans in a bid to discover its riches and mysteries."
</P>
<P>
China's tempo of development has completely changed thanks to a
revolution led by late leader Mao Zedong and other eminent
personalities like late Prime Minister Zhou Enlai 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In the last 50 years, China has become stronger as a united
country under one strong administration. "During the past 50
years China has been able to acquire modern technology in all
fields comparable to other advanced states in the world," he said.
"These include advances in atomic energy, jet technology,
computers and automation.
</P>
<P>
"It is significant that China has become modernized without
losing its cultural heritage and knowledge. In other words,
Chinese characteristics have not changed as a result of
modernization."
</P>
<P>
Mwinyi, who was the president of Tanzania between 1985 and 1995,
said it is also significant that China has been able to adopt
principles of establishing private enterprises in the economy
without losing the main tenets of national unity, and equality of
opportunity for all its people.
</P>
<P>
"Due to China's economic development, the country with 1.2
billion people is now the largest market in the world that no
serious business person can afford to ignore."
</P>
<P>
Despite its achievements, he said, China still has challenges
both at home and abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Former President Says Modern China in Shape (Part II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Domestically, he said, China needs to keep up the pace of
economic restructuring and modernization, while maintaining high
efficiency and productivity as well as low levels of inflation and
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"China will also need to keep on improving the quality of both
urban and rural life," said Mwinyi.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, he said that Tanzania and many other
African states do understand the sensitivity and truth about it,
and are therefore ardent supporters of the "one China policy."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that some countries are hypocritical on the
issue: on one hand they support divisive elements in other
countries, and on the other they do not want the same thing to
happen within their own territory.
</P>
<P>
Mwinyi said people in Taiwan would eventually abandon the
divisive elements and demand reunion with their brothers and
sisters on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
"After all, the current trend in the world today is to unite,
not otherwise," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I think everyone recognizes the regional and international role
of China after it became the bedrock of stabilization efforts
following the financial crisis last year in the Far East," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mwinyi said China is destined to grow stronger in the next
millennium and will be indeed a power to be reckoned with. He
dismissed fears that a strong China would pose threats to the
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relationship, he said, Tanzania and China have had
excellent political and social relations that have been translated
into economic ties.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania's projects built with the aid of China, like
Mahonda Sugar Factory, Urafiki Textiles, and UFI-Farm Implements,
should be transformed into joint ventures between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, private companies and individuals from
both sides should be encouraged to forge joint ventures for mutual
benefit. The former president also invited Chinese businessmen to
invest in Tanzania's agriculture sector, which he said has a vast
potential. 
</P>
</TEXT>
