<HEADLINE> Lawer Seeks to Bail Out Detained Hamas Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The chief lawer of 21 detained
members of the militant Palestinian Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) in Jordan is seeking the release on bail of two of the
Hamas leaders.
</P>
<P>
Saleh Armouti, who heads a 60-man team defending the 21 Hamas
members arrested during a government crackdown on the radical
group, said he is seeking to bail out Hamas poliburo chief Khalid
Mishaal and spokesman Ibrahim Ghosheh.
</P>
<P>
The two men had undergone eight hours of interrogation after
they were arrested Wednesday upon their arrival in Amman from Iran.
</P>
<P>
Armouti said the Hamas members were being interrogated by
state security court Prosecutor General Mahmoud Obeidat, who
would decide whether they would be tried in a court.
</P>
<P>
Police had charged them with engaging in illegal political
activities, possession of weapons and holding military training as
part of their campaigns against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas is known as a radical and militant Palestinian
organization that opposes the peace process between Israel and the
Palestinians, and it has carried out several deadly attacks on
Israeli civilians in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas is still standing for a holy war "to liberate all
Palestinian territories" to establish an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's crackdown on Hamas came at a time when the peace
process on Israeli-Palestinian track is back on track following
the smooth implementation of revised agreement for the Wye Accord
and the start of the long-overdue final status talks.
</P>
<P>
The start of the final status talks, the most touchy point in
the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations, rekindled the hope of
finally achieving peace in the region. Under the new deal, a
permanent peace agreement should be concluded by September 20,
2000.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the only two Arab states that sign peace
treaty with Israel. It is a firm supporter for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The roundup of Hamas members were apparently preemptive
measures to pave the way, to some extent, for the critical and yet
vulnerable peace process between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
