<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Updates with details Hatoyama Elected New Leader of Japan's Largest Opposition Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Yukio Hatoyama was elected
Saturday as new president of Japan's main opposition Democratic
Party of Japan (DPJ), beating incumbent leader Naoto Kan in a
runoff ballot.
</P>
<P>
Hatoyama, the current deputy secretary general of the DPJ,
received 182 of the 314 votes cast in the runoff, while Kan got
130. Two votes were invalid.
</P>
<P>
The runoff was held as none of the three candidates in the DPJ
presidential contest won a majority in the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
In the first ballot, Hatoyama captured 154 votes out of 321
votes cast, seven votes short of the 161-vote majority needed for
a first-ballot victory. Kan got 109 while DPJ Executive Council
Chairman Takahiro Yokomichi, another candidate in the race, gained
57 votes.
</P>
<P>
A total of 321 people, 146 party lawmakers, 81 non-incumbent
DPJ candidates in the next general election and 94 representatives
of local DPJ branches, were eligible voters in the election.
</P>
<P>
Hatoyama, 52, comes from a wealthy political dynasty sometimes
dubbed Japan's version of the Kennedy family. His grandfather
Ichiro Hatoyama was Japan's prime minister from 1954 to 1956, and
his father Iichiro Hatoyama once served as Japan's foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
As new leader of the DPJ, Hatoyama will face the task of
uniting and invigorating the party to counter a new tripartite
coalition that Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, as president
of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), plans to launch with
the Liberal Party (LP) and the New Komeito party.
</P>
<P>
The proposed coalition would give the ruling bloc a majority in
the opposition-controlled House of Councilors, the upper house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Kan and Hatoyama co-headed the DPJ after launching the party in
September 1996. Kan became the party's sole leader in September
1997.
</P>
<P>
In April 1998, the party merged with three other opposition
parties under the DPJ banner, becoming Japan's largest opposition
party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebel Leaders Expected to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's rebel leader
Foday Sankoh and its ally former junta's ruler Johnny Koroma are
expected to return to the country's capital Freetown by October 1.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here from the city quoted a Sierra Leone
presidential aide as saying on Friday that President Tejan Kabbah
is to flag off a new government on or before October 1 which will
include the two in line with a peace accord signed on July 7 in
Togo's capital Lome.
</P>
<P>
The two rebel leaders' continued absence from Sierra Leone has
caused great concern for the governments of its West African
neighbors who helped broker the Lome peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"What we don't know is whether Sankoh and Koroma will be
arriving from Monrovia (the Liberian capital) together. But both
men will be in Freetown before October 1," the aide said.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh's will is to get the position of chairman of a national
minerals commission with the rank of vice-president, while
Koroma, who launched a military coup and ousted the elected Kabbah
for nine months from May 1997 will take charge of a national
commission overseeing the implementation of the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Aides to Sankoh said in Ivory Coast on Friday that his leader
will leave there for Liberia Sunday on his way home to help
implement the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, Sankoh started his tour of "visiting old
friends" on his way back to Freetown which is proved to be very
long despite the international community's repeated calling for
him to return to step up the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, who had fought the government since 1991, remain
armed despite the related stipulations in Lome peace accord that
they should be demilitarized in mid August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
