<HEADLINE> Former U.N. Secretary General Signs "Peace Scroll" by Chinese Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua)-- Boutros Boutros Ghali, the
visiting former secretary-general of the United Nations, signed
here on Friday a long "scroll for peace," or rather a Chinese boy'
s proposal for halting production of all toy weapons.
</P>
<P>
In May of 1995, the five-year-old Tao Yuan in the northernmost
Chinese province of Heilongjiang, wrote to Ghali, then U.N.
secretary-general, proposing to halt the production of all toy
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Ghali replied his letter and appreciated and expressed his
support to the Chinese boy's proposal. Since then, a total of 133
foreign ambassadors to China and representatives from 15 Beijing-
based U.N. organizations have signed the proposal, which has
become 10 meters long and is named as a "Peace Scroll".
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Ghali said he remembered very well
he wrote a reply to Tao Yuan. And he once again paid his attention
to and expressed his concern over the issue of children
development worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Ghali is currently on a visit to China at the invitation of the
United Nations Association of China.  
</P>
