<HEADLINE> Kenya's Processing Zones Increase Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Export Processing
Zones recorded an all-time high export of 2.4 billion shillings
(around 40 million U.S. dollars) during the 1998 financial year
(from July 1998 to June 1999) , the East African Standard
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Peter Muthoka, chief executive of the Export Promotion Council,
was quoted as saying that the 1998 exports increased by 30 percent
against that of the previous year standing at 1.9 billion
shillings.
</P>
<P>
He said the export processing zones are potential growth areas,
 especially for agro-based industries.
</P>
<P>
While outlining the country's prospects for future export, the
chief executive said that 50 percent of the exports from the zones
are destined to the market of the United States, considering that
a quota restriction has been imposed on textile goods from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
About 34 percent of the zones' exports head to the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa, he added.
</P>
<P>
Muthoka noted that following the success of Kenya's export
processing zones, several other African countries have started
similar zones.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to take such measures as reviewing the
agriculture policies if Kenya is to maintain its competitive edge
on its exports.
</P>
<P>
Those outdated agriculture policies should be discarded to
ensure Kenya to keep its competitiveness in horticulture and other
agro-based exports, Muthoka said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
