<HEADLINE> FAO Chief to Inspect Food Program in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Diouf, director
general of the United Nations Food and Agricultural Organization
(FAO), is scheduled to arrive here next Tuesday for a two-day
field visit.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Diouf will review the progress of the Special
Program on Food Security (SPFS) in the east African country,
reported The Guardian, a leading newspaper in Tanzania, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
FAO, headquartered in Rome, Italy, launched this program in mid
1990s in the low-income food-deficit countries to enhance their
national food security.
</P>
<P>
The FAO country representative in Tanzania, Sulayman M'boob,
said that Diouf will lead a high-level delegation of more than 50
people from FAO member countries.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will comprise agriculture ministers,
ambassadors, permanent representatives of FAO member nations,
representatives of leading donor organizations and representatives
of international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
M'boob said here Friday that the FAO chief and his delegation
will visit projects under SPFS in Morogoro Region in central
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, SPFS is divided into two phases. The first phase,
during 1995 and 1998, had its core activities implemented in 26
demonstration areas in Morogoro, M'boob said.
</P>
<P>
It involves increasing production and productivity of maize
and rice, cash crops and vegetables and increasing farm incomes
through diversification activities such as livestock improvement
and fish farming.
</P>
<P>
The program in Tanzania, involving 1,116 farmers, has been the
most successful in all food deficit countries, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
