<HEADLINE> Philippine Leader Calls Economy Stable Amid Peso Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Saturday that the economic situation in his
country remains stable despite the depreciation of the peso along
with other currencies in the Asian region in recent trading
sessions.
</P>
<P>
In a weekly radio-TV program here, Estrada said the peso is far
better than other Asian currencies, particularly the baht of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason for concern. That's the way business goes.
But, I am sure our economy is more stable," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said the Central Bank of the Philippines and
other concerned government agencies are helping him keep watch on
the peso's situation.
</P>
<P>
During the trading session Friday, the peso dropped to a low of
40.9 to the U.S. dollar, its lowest in more than 10 months.
</P>
<P>
"The peso depreciation doesn't stem from government control. It
is due to external forces," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a radio
interview here Saturday that the central bank remains confident
the peso will bounce back soon and the economy will "recover" some
ground it has lost. 
