<HEADLINE> U.N. Observers Arrive in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A team of the United Nations
military observers has arrived in Kampala, capital of Uganda, to
observe the cease- fire in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC).
</P>
<P>
The team is said to be part of the 400-plus U.N. troops to be
deployed in the capitals of the five countries involved in the DRC
conflict, the Monitor newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Minister of Defense Steven Kavuma reportedly confirmed
that the team was already in Kampala, but he did not give the
exact number of the cease-fire observers although a security
source put the number at 100.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U. N. announced that between 100 and 400 military
liaison officers would be based in the DRC, Angola, Namibia,
Zimbabwe, Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire accord, signed separately on July 10 and August
31, provides for the parties in the war to remain in their
positions pending a U.N. deployment, withdrawal of foreign troops
allied with Kinshasa and the rebels, an inter-Congolese national
dialogue and the facilitators for negotiations. 
</P>
