<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Underground Fire at U.S. Toxic Landfill Burns out of Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 24 (Xinhua) -- An underground fire at a
landfill about 100 miles east of Atlanta, the United States,
burned out of control Friday, environmental authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The 120-acre site consists of hundreds of underground trenches
filled with hazardous waste and toxic materials dumped for nearly
50 years. The authorities said they do not know exactly how
dangerous the fumes generated by the fire are to human life.
</P>
<P>
The landfill, which opened in the early 1940s, was closed in
1991 under court order because of the tremendous amount of toxic
waste that had been stored there over the years.
</P>
<P>
The trenches over the years were covered with layers of topsoil
while new trenches were dug on top of the old ones so that more
materials could be stored at the site, said Vince Dollard, of the
Georgia Environmental Protection Division.
</P>
<P>
The result has been that as the underground fire burns, it
releases fumes through pockets that have developed between the
crisscrossed trenches.
</P>
<P>
The fire, discovered on September 9, intensified earlier this
week. A residential neighborhood runs along the perimeter of the
landfill site, so the environmental agency has installed monitors
to measure toxicity.
</P>
<P>
Dollard said the state agency has contacted companies that
dumped materials at the site, and they have agreed to pay for
firefighting expenses, estimated at 20,000 U.S. dollars a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
