<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Key Sectors 70 pct Y2K ready: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' seven
mission-critical sectors are more than 70 percent Y2K-ready, the
National Security Council (NSC) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the NSC, the seven sectors are utilities,
telecommunications, transportation, finance, health care,
manufacturing and government.
</P>
<P>
In a report published here, the NSC said that the finance
sector is 95 percent ready for the Y2K; telecommunications, 81
percent; utilities and manufacturing, both 80 percent;
transportation, 79 percent; government, 77 percent; and health
care, 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among those institutions with 100 percent Y2K readiness are the
Central Bank of the Philippines and private banks in the country,
as well as the Manila Electric Co. and the oil sector, while the
National Power Corp. is 95 percent ready, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The NSC said that government agencies, such as the Government
Service Insurance System (GSIS), Social Security System (SSS),
Bureau of Internal Revenue, Bureau of Customs and Bureau of
Treasury are in the final stages of their preparations.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem, also known as the millennium bug, is a
computer glitch resulting from the use of two digits, instead of
four, to represent the year, which could lead to computer systems
mistaking the year 2000 for 1900, hence jeopardizing operations of
computer-dependent industries.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has set September 30 as the deadline
for all the seven mission-critical sectors to submit their Y2K
readiness reports to the Presidential Commission On Year 2000
Compliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
