<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM's Doctrine Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) --Australian prime minister
John Howard's newly produced doctrine has been criticized sharply
in his own country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local media earlier this week, John Howard
announced his doctrine, which seeks for Australia a status of the
United State's "deputy" in the region and a more important role in
dealing with the regional affairs, while pushing Australia's value
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
According to the Weekend Australian daily Saturday, Australian
National University security expert Alan Dupont said that "this
deputy sheriff notion is absolute nonsense. It would be totally
counter-productive. It sends all the wrong messages to the region
and reinforces the idea that we are just proxies of the U.S."
</P>
<P>
David Mcgibbon, a former Liberal senator and chairman of the
Joint Parliament Foreign Affairs Committee, said that "the real
danger we face in all this is being seen as a pot-colonial relic,
isolated from Asia in a corner of the Pacific. It's very easy to
run the campaign against Australia that we are isolated in
Asia...."
</P>
<P>
Successive Australian governments had adopted a regional policy
to try to close, melt into and finally become an Asian country and
they established special relationships with Asia. But Prime
minister John Howard plays down any special ties with Asia and
Asian countries, saying that Australia possesses too many special
relations which he believed are not based on the national interest
of Australia.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister had said after taking office in 1996 that
identifying the country's station geographically is "meaningless"
and the native ties with the West is a "wealth" for Australia. He
made clear that his policy in this area is "to stand along with
the West to deal with Asia." 
</P>
</TEXT>
