<HEADLINE> French Life Insurer Keen on Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Patrice Forget, member of the
Executive Board of CNP Assurances S.A., the No.1 life insurer in
France, has described China as one of the most important emerging
life insurance markets in the world.
</P>
<P>
Forget, who visited Beijing as a member of a French trade
delegation, made the comment in an interview with Xinhua during
his Beijing stay.
</P>
<P>
He said his company is very interested in the Chinese market
and wishes to explore it together with Chinese insurers in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1850, CNP is the leading one among France's 130 life
insurance companies. It reported a turnover of 18.1 billion U.S.
dollars and a net profit of 315 million dollars in 1998, with a
market share of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Forget said his company has chosen China as its foothold into
the Asia market, because it has a huge population, but its life
insurance market is only one eighth of the French market, which
means the market has a great potential.
</P>
<P>
Christian Bisschop, chief representative in Beijing for both
CNP and the French Federation of Insurance Companies, said that
life insurance is just beginning in China, but the country's
housing and medical reforms would create a huge market space.
</P>
<P>
He said French life insurers have advantages in experience,
technology, management and development of new products, and are
willing to share such advantages with their Chinese counterparts.
</P>
