<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Exports Up, Deficit Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's trade deficit is
expected to narrow by 54 percent to 23 million U.S. dollars in the
first nine months of 1999 thanks to a rebound in exports and
stationary imports, English daily Vietnam News reported here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The country's value of exports in the first nine months is
expected to grow 17.2 percent to 8.186 billion U.S. dollars or
81.9 percent of the government's annual target.
</P>
<P>
The rebound of Vietnam's export is because of a recovery in
shipments of footwear products and an increase of the oil prices
in the world, according to Vietnam's General Statistical Office
(GSO).
</P>
<P>
Footwear exports grew 34.5 percent to 1.014 billion U.S.
dollars while garment exports grew 11.9 percent to 1.248 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil, Vietnam's No.3 export earner, rose 27.3 percent in
volume to 10.888 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Rice exports, at the fourth place, grew in volume by 22.4
percent to 3.823 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The country's value of imports for the period is expected to
fall 4.8 percent from the same period last year to 8.209 billion
U.S. dollars, representing 71.4 percent of the annual target,
narrowing the gap between imports and exports for the sixth
straight year.
</P>
<P>
According to the GSO, complete vehicles and spare parts imports
dropped most, down 27.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Machine and equipment imports fell nine percents while
pharmaceutical imports dropped by eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Cement clinker imports registered a 63 percent decline to
245,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
