<HEADLINE> Colombia Spends Over 1.5 Billion Dollars in Defending Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of
Colombia has spent 1.545 billion U.S. dollars in one year and a
half in defending its exchange band from speculators' inroads,
official sources said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in the last weeks it was forced to sell
210 million dollars from its international reserves to maintain
the dollar exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The dollar closed Thursday for a third consecutive day at a
historic low of 1,993.97 pesos per dollar, which forced the
central bank to pull out 142.5 million dollars to stop the
speculators.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, it intervened in the market with more than 1 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry said that speculative outbreaks must be
controlled, warning that those who promote speculation "must be
very careful, because they can suffer a big surprise."
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts said it will be impossible to continue
maintaining the exchange bands, because such attempts have taken
place for many times without positive results. 
</P>
