<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Eel Producers to Open Up More Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- China, the world's largest
producer of eels, is expecting the tasty fish to swim into more
streams across domestic and European markets.
</P>
<P>
China has produced 70 percent of the eels sold in the world
last year, and exported 48,000 tons of roast eels to Japan,
occupying 91 percent of its market, according to Lin Meijiao,
deputy director of the National Aquatic Technology Extension
Centre, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Small eels are a lucrative sector for China, noted Lin. China
produced 163,000 tons of eels in 1998, constituting a meagre 0.4
percent of China's total aquaculture production. While the
turnover reached 26 billion yuan (3.1 billion US dollars),
accounting for 10.3 percent of the total value generated by the
aquatic industry last year, statistics from the Ministry of
Agriculture indicate.
</P>
<P>
Eel exports exceeded 900 million US dollars in 1996, or 30
percent of the total foreign currency brought in by the
aquaculture sector.
</P>
<P>
However, lax control on the eel raising industry and heavy
dependence on the Japanese market have resulted in a host of
problems, Lin told a news conference yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the enterprises marketing eel fries and medicated food
for eels are located in the coastal regions, while eel raisers are
scattered in remote areas, she said.
</P>
<P>
Also too many firms are engaged in importing eel fries. Some
even resort to smuggling the product, causing a huge gap between
procurement and purchase prices, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The worst thing, since Japan is the world's largest eel
consumer, is that a multitude of Chinese enterprises have in the
past been involved in a price-cutting spree. This, coupled with
the fluctuation of the Japanese yen, has resulted in significant
losses to Chinese enterprises.
</P>
<P>
For example, in 1995, China exported 36,200 tons of roast eels
to Japan, valued at 860 million US dollars. However, when the
country's export surged to 53,000 tons in 1998, it only chalked up
620 million US dollars in foreign currency. This represented a 50.
8 percent slash in the price per kilogram, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
"Between 1997 and 1998, China's eel production was maintained
between 140,000 and 160,000 tons, while the Japanese market can
only consume a maximum of 120,000 tons," she said.
</P>
<P>
Experts and officials attending yesterday's press conference
said they believe market potential is huge in China. This optimism
calls for massive efforts.
</P>
<P>
At present, Chinese people consume only 40,000 tons of live
eels, and almost never eat roast eels, according to Liu Zaojun, a
fishery expert from Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The China Eel Industrial Association, which was founded last
year, should help discipline the eel market by curbing blind
import of eel fries and export of eels at low prices, and
promoting eel consumption among Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, training in eel raising and disease prevention is
also needed, noted Zhang Guosheng, deputy director of the Fujian
Provincial Fisheries Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
