<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Economy to Shrink 6.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan economy could
shrink 6.8 percent at the end of this year, as a result of the oil
sector crisis, the Finance Ministry said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report, "A Pessimistic Scenario for Economic Activity"
released by the ministry, said the country' gross domestic product
(GDP) would drop 12 percent and that of the non-oil sector 4.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan oil sector closed in 1998 with a one percent
drop and the non-oil sector 0.85 percent, respectively, which
resulted in a GDP drop of 0.7 percent, according to the annual
report from the Central Bank of Venezuela (BCV).
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the BCV showed that the Venezuelan economy
dropped 9.5 percent in the first half of 1999, compared to the
same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry's study said that the government of
President Chavez has reduced its expenditures this year by 10
percent to 23 billion dollars. One of the most important
expenditures is the payment of foreign public debt service, which
according to government estimations will be 1.626 billion dollars
in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The government expects that the increase of more than nine
dollars per barrel of oil will be reflected in a reduction of the
budget deficit of 3.6 percent of the GDP against an estimation of
6 percent at the beginning of the year, an approximate cut of 4.4
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
