<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Discontented With Status Quo of CIS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev voiced discontent Friday with the status quo of the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) in the Kazakh capital of
Astana, criticizing it for failing to promote regional economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
"The CIS is losing its sense as a cooperative organization," he
was quoted as saying by the Interfax News Agency. "The CIS is not
heading for integration but rather disintegration," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh president made the statement to reporters after
talking with government heads from Russia, Belarus, Kyrgyzstan and
Tajikistan, who met in Astana and signed a series of accords on
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The four countries plus Kazakhstan set up a customs union last
February in Moscow in an effort to survive the severe economic
aftermath incurred by Russia's financial crisis in addition to the
financial crises in Asia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the CIS integration should be an economic
integration in the first place, Nazarbayev said that however the
trade among CIS countries had shrunk 70 percent since 1991.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, he added, transcaucasian
countries saw their trade with CIS members down by 40 percent and
that with Kazakhstan 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he complained, CIS members have signed thousands of
documents, but only 5 to 10 percent of them had been implemented.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh president hoped that with concrete actions and
measures, the five-nation customs union will be able to set an
example for CIS integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
