<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Story of A Film Actress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year is the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China. Xinhua News Agency is
releasing about 50 stories on Chinese men and women, young and old,
to illustrate the changes that have taken place in China over the
past half century. These people will describe their lives and how
they fit into the changes in the motherland. This is the 33rd
story in the series.
</P>
<P>
NANNING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Former film star Huang Wanqiu
has become so ordinary she can now get lost in a crowd.
</P>
<P>
But over 30 years ago, she had thousands of fans in China and
overseas who loved her in her popular role as the village girl who
sang like a lark in the film "Third Sister Liu."
</P>
<P>
"A good actor should always present the most beautiful and
moving things and will be remembered by the audience no matter how
much time passes," said Huang, now 56, and mother of a grown-up
son and daughter.
</P>
<P>
During the turmoil of the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976),
Huang was persecuted and maltreated, but her life improved in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Huang says that the performing artists' political and economic
status has greatly improved and are respected by society since the
founding of New China in October 1949. In old China, however,
artists were scorned, she recalled.
</P>
<P>
The policies of reform and opening to the world over the past
two decades has revitalized China's artistic community. And
business has been brisk for investors involved in film, television,
calligraphy, the fine arts, and publishing.
</P>
<P>
With the help of local Party organizations and local
governments, Huang set up a range of businesses, and in the mid-
1980s started an art troupe funded with investment from overseas.
She heads the troupe, which has performed across the country and
toured overseas to spread Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
Huang, currently a member of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, pledged that
she would devote the remaining years of her life to teaching and
training more young Chinese performers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
