<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Opens Oil Prospection, Exploitation to Foreign Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso Friday signed concession contracts for 10
multinational firms to prospect and exploit oil and gas in 12
maritime zones of the country.
</P>
<P>
This ends almost half a century of monopoly by the state firm
Petroleos Brasilenos (Petrobras) in the prospection and
exploitation of oil and gas fields in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso signed the documents in the Pequena Gavea Palace in Rio
de Janeiro, saying that the participation of private interests
would permit the country to be self-sufficient in energy by the
year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Brazil needs 1.6 million barrels of oil every day, of which 500,
000 barrels must be imported.
</P>
<P>
The 10 multinational oil companies includes Yacimientos
Petroliferos Fiscales of Argentina, which is controlled by the
Spanish firm Repsol, Agip, Esso, Texaco, Unocal, British Petroleum,
British Borneo, Amarada Hess, Kerr-McGee and Shell.
</P>
<P>
The firms submitted their bids in a contest called last June by
the National Petroleum Agency (ANP) for activities in 27 zones in
the marine watersheds of Campos and Santos, and in the Amazonian
watershed.
</P>
<P>
The ANP will call a second bidding by the end of this year for
private interests in oil exploration. It has obtained 178 million
dollars from the bidding licenses for the 10 multinational firms.
</P>
<P>
Some of the prospection and exploitation projects will be
jointly implemented by Petrobras and multinational companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
