<DOCNO> XIE19990925.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing: From Local City To China's Fourth Municipality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-year-old Zhou
Yonglin is a native of the city of Chongqing but he often
complains that he can get lost whenever he goes out shopping or
just to have a walk.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's complaint is a reflection of the changes that have taken
place in this massive urban area over the past five decades.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing was referred to as the war-time capital by the
Kuomintang Government in 1940, and it made a great contribution to
the War of Resistance to Japan (1937-1945) as a political and
economic center. In the downtown area there is a monument to
victory in that war. For a long time it was the tallest building
in Chongqing, but it's now overshadowed by high-rises or taller
buildings.
</P>
<P>
After New China was founded, Chongqing became a political and
economic center in the southwest. In 1953, the central government
designated it a municipality directly under its jurisdiction. At
that time, the country's first jeep and first seamless steel
tubing and heavy rails were produced here and it was one of China'
s six largest industrial bases.
</P>
<P>
A year later, Chongqing became a city in Sichuan Province and,
by the 1960s and 1970s, large military-industry enterprises had
been moved to Chongqing as part of the State's strategic policies.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, Chongqing took the lead in an overall reform of the
economic system and had a kind of provincial status in managing
its economic affairs. Motor vehicles, metallurgy, and pharmacy
became its three pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
Then, in 1997, Chongqing again became a municipality, China's
fourth, after Beijing, Shanghai, and Tianjin, as an urban area
with a political status similar to that of a province. It covers
an area of 82,300 sq km. and has a population of 30 million, with
40 counties under its administrative control.
</P>
<P>
Changes in Chongqing can in fact be said to epitomize the
country's tremendous changes, according to Prof. Zhou Yong, who
has studied the city for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, Chongqing has built seven bridges across the
Yangtze and Jiangling rivers and five expressways and has spent 43
billion yuan (5.18 billion U.S. dollars) on some 4,000 km of
highways.
</P>
<P>
With improved infrastructure, Chongqing has become more
attractive to foreign investors. It approved more than 230
overseas-funded enterprises in 1997, with a total of 940 million U.
S. dollars worth of foreign funds. By the next year, 26 of the
world's top 500 enterprises were involved in projects here.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Chongqing is now one of China's major motor vehicle
producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
