<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Watson Wins Legal Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- British boxer Michael Watson,
who suffered brain damages during a fight in a world title bout in
1991, won a historic legal battle but his one million pound
damages claim against the British Boxing Board of Control is set
to throw the sport into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
After Justice Ian Kennedy ruled at the High Court in London
that the Board was liable for the boxer's damage incurred in the
fight against Chris Eubank, BBBC's QC, Ronald Walker, said it was
a"landmark decision".
</P>
<P>
"It is the first case in which a regulatory authority has been
held liable for the negligent failure to regulate, resulting in
damages."
</P>
<P>
But 34-year-old Watson's hopes of securing compensation for the
loss of his health and career could be threatened by the
revelation that the Board was uninsured against liability to its
members.
</P>
<P>
The Board's general secretary, John Morris, would not comment
on the suggestion that its finances were in a bad way.
</P>
<P>
He said: "I am not going to go into that. We are a non-profit
making organization, which was set up in 1929 by the will of the
people in boxing to conduct the sport."
</P>
<P>
"If we are not there to do it, then obviously it has to be
controlled.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very serious matter which will have to be given very
serious consideration."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Board would pursue an appeal even though the
judge refused leave.
</P>
<P>
He added: "The Board has always had considerable sympathy for
Michael Watson following the injuries he sustained in his contest
against Chris Eubank." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
