<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening to World Brings Economic Progress to North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Shanxi Province in north
China has now actually put to use a total of 2.76 billion U.S.
dollars of foreign funds, about 9 percent of the province's fixed
assets, according to Liu Zhenhua, acting provincial governor.
</P>
<P>
These foreign funds are a major component of the province's
fixed assets investment, and the accumulated foreign investment
from 1992 to 1998 was many times that of the 1978-1988 period.
</P>
<P>
"Great changes have taken place in the province for the past
two decades since the implementation of the country's reform and
opening policy," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Shanxi's gross domestic product (GDP) last
year exceeded 160 billion yuan (19.2 billion U.S. dollars), some
27 times that of 1952, in spite of price rise, and the annual
growth rate of its GDP has remained at an average of 9.8 percent
since 1978.
</P>
<P>
"The opening and reform policy has also provided us an
opportunity to attract foreign investment," he said, adding that
the first regulation issued by the central government on setting
up joint ventures in 1979 offered legal protection to foreign
businesses during their expansion in China.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the province has approved 1,982 foreign-funded
ventures, offering job opportunities to some 120,000 local people,
and export volume now accounts for 8 percent of the province's
total.
</P>
<P>
Some 42 countries and regions including the United States,
Japan, Singapore, the Republic of Korea (ROK), and Hong Kong and
Taiwan, have invested mainly in quality highway construction, the
electric power industry, and large water conservancy projects,
said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, agriculture has become another hot area for
investment, with total overseas investment in the last six years
reaching as much as 600 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen countries and regions, along with a number of
international organizations, have shown their keen interest in the
province's agriculture over the past two years, and investment in
this area now amounts to 960 million yuan (11.52 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Liu went on to say that Shanxi will intensify cooperation with
foreign investors in infrastructure, hi-tech industries,
environmental projects, and agricultural development, and they
will also be encouraged to become involved in the reform of large-
and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, the central government's special attention to
economic growth in the mid-western China in these past few years
has also brought us great opportunities for further development,"
added Liu.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi Province, located in north China, is a typical inland
province hemmed in by mountains. Though rich in mineral resources,
coal in particular, the lack of communication with the outside
hindered it from further development in the past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
