<HEADLINE> Mexican Emigrants to United States Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 300,000 Mexicans
emigrated to the United States in the last three years, seeking
better opportunities, Mexico's National Migration Institute (INM)
commissioner Alejandro Carrillo Castro said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mexicans' emigration to the United States dated back decades,
but increased considerably in the last 20 years, Carrillo told the
press in the port city of Veracruz, in the state of the same name,
300 kilometers east of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
He said that better paid jobs in the United States are the main
attraction for the low-income Mexican labor force.
</P>
<P>
The director of the INM, a branch of the Interior Ministry,
went to Veracruz to take part in the Fifth National Meeting of
Public Administration Institutes.
</P>
<P>
The states which register the biggest exodus of Mexicans to the
United States are, according to Carrillo, Michoacan, Jalisco,
Durango, Zacatecas, and San Luis Potosi.
</P>
<P>
The United States deports thousands of undocumented foreigners,
most of them Mexicans, followed by nationals from Central American
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
