<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Currency Devaluation Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ecuadoran exchange market
continued boiling Friday when the U.S. dollar parity surpassed the
15,000 sucre barrier.
</P>
<P>
The dollar quotation closed Friday at 13,050 sucres for
purchase and 15,300 sucres for sale in the Banco de Pichincha, one
of the biggest banks in this country, going to an average of
14,175 sucres, which meant a 1.6 percent increase over the 13,945
sucres Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar quotation Thursday was 13,800 sucres buy and 14,090
sell.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Ecuador (BCE) blamed on speculative factors
the pressures of the last days on the rate of exchange.
</P>
<P>
The BCE published Friday a communique reminding the economic
agents that speculative pressures distort the prospects of
macroeconomic order the country is striving for, especially the
maintained reduction of inflation.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador is facing its worst economic slump. The South American
country is technically in default of its 5.9 billion dollars in
Brady bonds. The government is working on a plan to restructure
the debts in an effort to reduce its total debt burden of 16
billion dollars, representing 110 percent of its gross domestic
product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
